<!-- When it seemed like I finally had the opportunity to work on the literal Primer, I froze. There were people sitting in the same building working on it, and I wanted to be as far from it as possible. This from a girl who spent the last decade hyper-optimizing her life, and constantly dreaming of automation and taking as much work off her hands as possible. What was going on? -->

An important part of the Primer is that lessons are tailored to the individual. Summarizing a news article requires knowing what the reader is hoping to come away from the article with. If they're looking for the facts of the case, which facts were relevant, and what was a fact? A single summary could not give you the salient takeaways. Actually, it's the opposite, communicating all interesting parts of an article might require expanding the article to bring in additional context. So while the Primer was maybe the inspiration, the actual products that were deployed set their goals much shorter than surfacing tailored information to the reader. The language tools that have flown closest to this are: SmartSummaries that mine your emails for actionable takeaways^[cite, and give example], or predictive coding^[cite, microsoft / openai]^[There are many other AI-based language products, like AI Dungeon that are astounding and wildly transformative.].

At work and at weekend, SF parties, I waded through conversations: "Wouldn't it be so cool if we could...," "Oh! And then we could..." 
<!-- Probably need more on this -->
And I then I would respond with how I wasn't sure how we could possibly create whatever the latest thing was while 

I spent two years only seeing the potential dangers. Instead of "yes, and" I was saying "sure, but." "I suppose you could do that, but have you considered...."
Am I just trying to justify what is impossible to justify?
Is it completely morally corrupt?
For a moment there, I believed that you could make anything sound plausible. I felt completely unmoored from morals. The seeming ease with which people around me crafted narratives that for the first five minutes sounded exciting made me doubt the validity of everything. 

And so come with me for a moment as we spiral down "sure, but." Sure, but how much data would we have to collect about someone in order to tailor a summary to them? Couldn't it be a violation of their privacy? Sure, but learning is awfully close to persuasion, and persuasion is a dangerous, powerful tool. Sure, but who gets to decide what's important for people to learn? Shouldn't that decision be made by the community?
<!-- Sure, but isn't it a violation of people's privacy to try to understand them so well that we can tailor a summary to them? -->

Around me, "yes, and"s swirled, and I felt like I was living in another dimension. How come they were allowed to have fun with their work? How come they weren't thinking about the "but"s. I wanted to have fun with my work. Somehow in the decade between my first foray into programming and being confronted with the opportunity to realize my dreams, I didn't know if I wanted it anymore. I just hadn't vocalized it to myself, or to others.
If no one else was talking about it, was I just being needlessly cautious^[No, people were talking about it. I just hadn't met them yet]?
I guess this is what privilege looks like.
I didn't realize how important "yes, and" was to brainstorming. I didn't realize that not doing it was keeping me from having fun, from actually enjoying my work, and from being invested in it.
"Sure, but"s are incredibly important, it's just worth it to go a little 

I wasn't the only "sure, but" in the room as I soon found out. 

